Mirrors CSAGenerator's emission (csa-generator.cc:490-523). Torque's
`%MakeLazy<T>('<getter>', args...)` intrinsic lowers to a
MakeLazyNodeInstruction; the kCCBuiltins backend now emits
`std::function<Tagged<T>()>` bound by value-capture of the visible
stack state. The lambda body invokes the getter macro via its
CCName() (for Torque macros, the default `TqRuntime<name>` — no
leading `state_` / `isolate`, matching kCC convention).

Lazy<T> has no constexpr version, so `GetRuntimeType()` null-derefs
(hits `ConstexprVersion()->GetGeneratedTypeName()`). Use
`Type::MatchUnaryGeneric(result_type, GetLazyGeneric())` to pull the
wrapped T and build `std::function<<T-runtime-type>()>` directly.

For Phase 3's "parses" acceptance bar this is sufficient; the
`TqRuntime_<getter>` function signature will be emitted by the kCC
pass in a later phase to make the output also linkable.
---
 deps/v8/src/torque/cc-generator.cc | 33 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 32 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/deps/v8/src/torque/cc-generator.cc b/deps/v8/src/torque/cc-generator.cc
index ac2e28a6..f6f17c04 100644
--- a/deps/v8/src/torque/cc-generator.cc
+++ b/deps/v8/src/torque/cc-generator.cc
@@ -320,7 +320,38 @@ void CCGenerator::EmitInstruction(
 
 void CCGenerator::EmitInstruction(const MakeLazyNodeInstruction& instruction,
                                   Stack<std::string>* stack) {
-  ReportError("Not supported in C++ output: MakeLazyNode");
+  // Mirrors CSAGenerator's emission (csa-generator.cc:490-523), producing a
+  // std::function<Tagged<T>()> bound by value-capture of the visible stack
+  // state. The lambda body invokes the getter macro via the same
+  // CCName()/CallCsaMacroInstruction convention used elsewhere in cc-output
+  // (no leading `state_` or `isolate` argument — those are CSA / builtin-
+  // linkage specific). For Phase 3 this only needs to parse; the referenced
+  // `TqRuntime_<getter>` function is emitted by the kCC pass and will be
+  // linked together with the kCCBuiltins output in a later phase.
+  TypeVector parameter_types =
+      instruction.macro->signature().parameter_types.types;
+  std::vector<std::string> args = ProcessArgumentsCommon(
+      parameter_types, instruction.constexpr_arguments, stack);
+
+  std::string result_name =
+      DefinitionToVariable(instruction.GetValueDefinition());
+  stack->Push(result_name);
+
+  // `Type::GetRuntimeType()` would null-deref on `Lazy<T>` (no constexpr
+  // version). `AbstractType::GetGeneratedTypeName()` special-cases the Lazy
+  // generic, but returns `std::function<TNode<T>()>` (CSA form). For CC
+  // output we need `std::function<<T-runtime-type>()>` to match the lambda
+  // body, so construct it directly from the wrapped type's runtime form.
+  std::optional<const Type*> lazy_wrapped = Type::MatchUnaryGeneric(
+      instruction.result_type, TypeOracle::GetLazyGeneric());
+  CHECK(lazy_wrapped.has_value());
+  decls() << "  std::function<" << (*lazy_wrapped)->GetRuntimeType()
+          << "()> " << result_name << ";  USE(" << result_name << ");\n";
+
+  out() << "  " << result_name << " = [=]() { return "
+        << instruction.macro->CCName() << "(";
+  PrintCommaSeparatedList(out(), args);
+  out() << "); };\n";
 }
 
 void CCGenerator::EmitInstruction(const CallBuiltinInstruction& instruction,
