From 4770054d2ab870c3090a4a317739d187530487a7 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Brandon Payton <brandon@happycode.net>
Date: Thu, 23 Apr 2026 17:56:39 -0400
Subject: [PATCH 58/59] torque: kCCBuiltins wraps macro bodies in
 V8_INTERNAL_DEFINED_ guards
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Torque emits each TorqueMacro body into both the kCC -tq-inl.inc
(inline definition, include-guarded) and the kCCBuiltins
-tq-ccbuiltins.cc (inline definition). The kCC pass already wraps
its emission in `#ifndef V8_INTERNAL_DEFINED_<CCName> ... #endif`
so multiple -tq-inl.inc headers transitively included into one TU
don't produce a redefinition. The kCCBuiltins pass previously skipped
this guard, reasoning that inline cross-TU duplicates were ODR-legal.

That reasoning misses the within-TU case: the kCCBuiltins preamble
pulls in `casting-inl.h`, `heap-object-inl.h`, `js-array-inl.h`, …,
and via the class-inl.h → class-tq-inl.inc chain, a -tq-inl.inc for
the SAME macro may already be visible in the current TU. The
kCCBuiltins inline body emitted into the SAME TU is then a second
definition — a redefinition error even though both are inline.

Task 5.8 ArrayIsArray surfaced this for
TqRuntimeFromConstexpr_intptr_constexpr_int31_0 (previous definition
in fixed-array-tq-inl.inc:51 via the transitive js-array-inl.h →
fixed-array-inl.h → fixed-array-tq-inl.inc chain) and
TqRuntimeFromConstexpr_uint32_constexpr_uint32_0 (scope-info).

Fix: apply the same V8_INTERNAL_DEFINED_<CCName> guard to the
kCCBuiltins emission. If a transitive -tq-inl.inc already defined
the macro, the kCCBuiltins body is skipped (first-seen wins). If
not, the kCCBuiltins body is the definition for this TU, and any
later inclusion of a -tq-inl.inc is guarded out. Same-guard-name
design is intentional — it's one symbol, one definition per TU, by
whichever pass gets there first.

This closes Task 5.8 defect (8).
---
 deps/v8/src/torque/implementation-visitor.cc | 14 ++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 10 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/deps/v8/src/torque/implementation-visitor.cc b/deps/v8/src/torque/implementation-visitor.cc
index c19c2d52..69077a94 100644
--- a/deps/v8/src/torque/implementation-visitor.cc
+++ b/deps/v8/src/torque/implementation-visitor.cc
@@ -423,11 +423,17 @@ void ImplementationVisitor::VisitMacroCommon(Macro* macro) {
   } else if (output_type_ == OutputType::kCCDebug) {
     include_guard.emplace(&csa_cc,
                           "V8_INTERNAL_DEFINED_"s + macro->CCDebugName());
+  } else if (output_type_ == OutputType::kCCBuiltins) {
+    // Use the same guard as kCC (same CCName()): if the kCC -tq-inl.inc
+    // for this macro is transitively included into the current
+    // -tq-ccbuiltins.cc TU (via any of the preamble's *-inl.h headers
+    // → class-inl.h → class-tq-inl.inc chains), its definition wins and
+    // ours is skipped. Without this guard, the same TU has two inline
+    // definitions of the macro — a redefinition error, even though
+    // both are `inline` and token-identical (C++ requires exactly one
+    // definition per TU; `inline` only relaxes the cross-TU ODR rule).
+    include_guard.emplace(&csa_cc, "V8_INTERNAL_DEFINED_"s + macro->CCName());
   }
-  // kCCBuiltins: no include-guard. The body is emitted as `inline`
-  // (see GenerateFunction's SetInlineDefinition call); cross-TU
-  // duplicates with the kCC -tq-inl.inc emission are ODR-legal
-  // because both are `inline` and token-identical.
 
   f.PrintBeginDefinition(csa_ccfile());
 
